Q40. (Theory) Explain QoS (Quality of Service) levels in MQTT: QoS 0 (At most once), 
QoS 1 (At least once), QoS 2 (Exactly once). In an IoT water level monitoring system, 
which QoS level would you choose and why? (2 marks) 

QoS 0 – At Most Once

In this level, the message is sent only once and there is no confirmation from the receiver. 
If the message is lost during transmission, it is not sent again. This level provides the fastest communication with the least network overhead.

QoS 1 – At Least Once

In this level, the sender waits for an acknowledgment from the receiver. 
If no acknowledgment is received, the message is retransmitted. This ensures that the message reaches the receiver, but it may be delivered more than once.

QoS 2 – Exactly Once

This is the highest level of reliability. It uses a four-step handshake process to ensure that the message is delivered exactly one time without duplication. However, it requires more bandwidth and processing.


For an IoT water level monitoring system, I would choose QoS 1 (At Least Once). 
Water level data is important and should reach the monitoring system reliably. 
QoS 1 ensures that messages are delivered even if the network connection is unstable. 
Although duplicate messages may occur, they can be easily handled by the application. 
QoS 0 is less reliable, while QoS 2 adds unnecessary overhead for this type of monitoring system.
